<dl id="n53075b"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n53" href="#n53075b">N53 (VI.B.46)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n53all.htm#n53075b"> 75(b)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> ogma (sunface) ~ <small>Green</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n53075b"><li>FW 89.32 </li><li><a href="../../flex/d/lexd.htm#n53075b">2010</a> </li><li><a href="../../flex/d/l39d.htm#n53075b">1939</a> </li><li><ms href="#n53075b">MS BL 47476a-196</ms> </li><li>JJA 49:413 <a name="dd10" href="../../ff/fdra/dda.htm#dd10">Usage</a> </li><li> <a href="../../flex/d/dd10.htm#n53075b">Draft: I.4&sect;1.10</a>/2.10</li> </ul> <blockquote class="sources">&lsquo;Ogham&rsquo;, says the treatise on the subject which we find in <cite>The Book of Ballymote</cite>, &lsquo;was put together by <mark>Ogma Sun-face</mark>, son of Bres, son of Elada.&lsquo; This conducts us into august company. Whatever the author of the treatise may have supposed, there is no shadow of a doubt that Ogma was originally a god. He was one of the Tuatha De Danann, the numerous pagan gods of the Goidelic people, whose complicated <i>theogonia</i>, euhemerized into a bald string of genealogies, is made into an &lsquo;invasion&rsquo; of Ireland in the history of the country concocted and taught in the native schools. <small> R.A. Stewart MacAlister, <a name="MSLI" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#MSLI"><cite title="source">The Secret Languages of Ireland</cite></a> (Jan 1937) Ogham, 29</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
